The '''Future Attack Reconnaissance Aircraft''' ('''FARA''') program was initiated by the [[United States Army]] in 2018 to develop a successor to the [[Bell OH-58 Kiowa]] [[scout helicopter]] as part of the [[Future Vertical Lift]] program. The OH-58 was retired in 2017; three prior programs for a successor were cancelled prior to reaching production: [[Light Helicopter Experimental]] (1982–2004, resulting in the [[Boeing–Sikorsky RAH-66 Comanche]]), Armed Reconnaissance Helicopter (2004–06, resulting in the [[Bell ARH-70 Arapaho]]), and [[Armed Aerial Scout]] (2012–13, evaluating commercial off-the-shelf designs). Several billions of dollars were spent without delivering any new helicopters to service, due to this cycle of development and cancellation. During this time the armed scout role was filled primarily by the Vietnam-era OH-58, which was finally retired in the late 2010s, leaving the Army to use attack helicopters to fill in this role. 

Design contracts for FARA candidates were awarded in April 2019 to five manufacturers: AVX Aircraft (in partnership with [[L3Harris Technologies]]), [[Bell Helicopter]], [[Boeing]], [[Karem Aircraft]], and [[Sikorsky Aircraft]] (part of [[Lockheed Martin]] now). In March 2020, the designs from Bell and Sikorsky were selected to proceed to Phase 2 of the competition, expected to end with a government flight test evaluation in fall 2023,<ref>{{cite news |author=Tate |first=Sarah |date=25 March 2020 |title=Future Vertical Lift: Army selects Future Attack Reconnaissance Aircraft prototype performers |url=https://www.army.mil/article/234002/future_vertical_lift_army_selects_future_attack_reconnaissance_aircraft_prototype_performers |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200326124532/https://www.army.mil/article/234002/future_vertical_lift_army_selects_future_attack_reconnaissance_aircraft_prototype_performers |archive-date=26 March 2020 |access-date=26 March 2020 |work=U.S. Army}}</ref> followed by the selection of a successor by 2028.<ref name=DN-190423/> However, on 8 February 2024, the U.S. Army announced that the FARA program would be terminated due to developments in [[modern warfare]] rendering it unnecessary.<ref name=":0">{{cite news |last1=Everstine |first1=Brian |last2=Trimble |first2=Steve |title=U.S. Army Cancels FARA In Overhaul Of Aviation Plans |url=https://aviationweek.com/defense-space/budget-policy-operations/us-army-cancels-fara-overhaul-aviation-plans |access-date= 10 February 2024 |work=Aviation Week Intelligence Network |publisher=Informa Markets |date= 8 February 2024}}</ref><ref name= rightCall >Jen Judson [https://www.defensenews.com/land/2024/02/12/army-was-right-to-kill-multibillion-dollar-helo-program-analysts-say/ (12 February 2024) Army was right to kill multibillion-dollar helo program, analysts say]</ref>

==Design goals==
[[File:OH-58D 2.jpg|thumb|FARA was intended to develop a successor to the OH-58 in the armed reconnaissance role (''pictured'')]]
U.S. Army officials described FARA as the "knife-fighter" of future Army aviation capabilities, intended to deliver high performance in a compact aircraft. Under the initial request for proposals, FARA candidates were to use the engine selected through the [[Improved Turbine Engine Program]] (ITEP). Performance goals imposed relatively few constraints beyond overall dimensions, with maximum rotor diameter and fuselage width each not to exceed {{convert|40|ft}}.<ref name="DN-181003" /> The proposed aircraft was expected to integrate government-furnished equipment (including weapons and the engine), align with affordability objectives, and meet desired range, endurance, and payload targets.<ref>{{cite news |last=Crum |first=Kerensa |date=April 29, 2019 |title=Future Attack Reconnaissance Aircraft Competitive Prototype program progresses ahead of schedule |url=https://www.army.mil/article/221077/future_attack_reconnaissance_aircraft_competitive_prototype_program_progresses_ahead_of_schedule |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230929163106/https://www.army.mil/article/221077/future_attack_reconnaissance_aircraft_competitive_prototype_program_progresses_ahead_of_schedule |archive-date=September 29, 2023 |access-date=October 15, 2019 |work=U.S. Army}}</ref>

==Competition history==
The OH-58 was retired without a clear successor in 2014; three successive programs were cancelled without reaching production; although the Army intended to perform a service life extension program for the OH-58 fleet in 2013, cuts to the defense budget forced its retirement. In lieu of the OH-58, the Army has used [[Boeing AH-64 Apache]] attack helicopters paired with [[AAI RQ-7 Shadow]] drones in the armed reconnaissance role.<ref>{{cite news |author=Judson |first=Jen |date=28 April 2017 |title=Armed reconnaissance still biggest gap in US Army aviation |url=https://www.defensenews.com/digital-show-dailies/aaaa/2017/04/28/armed-reconnaissance-still-biggest-gap-in-us-army-aviation/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://archive.today/20240110035514/https://www.defensenews.com/digital-show-dailies/aaaa/2017/04/28/armed-reconnaissance-still-biggest-gap-in-us-army-aviation/ |archive-date=10 January 2024 |access-date=15 October 2019 |work=Defense News}}</ref>

FARA is part of the [[Future Vertical Lift]] program and its procurement is largely modeled on the [[Joint Multi-Role]] technology demonstration program. The US Army released a draft solicitation on June 22, 2018 for reconnaissance helicopter proposals, with the intent to have two flying prototype designs by 2023, which will compete for the final award.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.defensenews.com/land/2018/06/22/us-army-shoots-to-get-future-attack-recon-helicopter-prototype-flying-by-2023/ |title=US Army aims to get attack recon helicopter prototype flying by 2023 |author=Judson, Jen |date=June 22, 2018 |work=Defense News |access-date=15 October 2019}}</ref><ref name=TheDrive>{{cite news |url=https://www.thedrive.com/the-war-zone/21760/army-lays-out-plans-for-pilot-optional-knife-fighter-attack-reconnaissance-rotorcraft |title=Army Lays Out Plans For Pilot-Optional 'Knife Fighter' Attack Reconnaissance Rotorcraft |author=Trevithick, Joseph |date=June 25, 2018 |work=The Drive |access-date=15 October 2019}}</ref> On October 3, 2018, the Army released its formal request for proposal and outlined its proposed schedule:<ref name="DN-181003">{{cite news |author=Judson |first=Jen |date=3 October 2018 |title=US Army triggers design competition for future attack reconnaissance helicopter |url=https://www.defensenews.com/land/2018/10/03/us-army-triggers-design-competition-for-future-attack-reconnaissance-helicopter/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://archive.today/20240110035325/https://www.defensenews.com/land/2018/10/03/us-army-triggers-design-competition-for-future-attack-reconnaissance-helicopter/ |archive-date=10 January 2024 |access-date=15 October 2019 |work=Defense News}}</ref>
* Jun 2019: Award four to six initial candidate design contracts
* Mar 2020: Choose two of the initial candidate designs to be developed into flying prototypes
* Nov 2022: Fly-off competition to be held between the two prototype designs
* Future: Award contract based on results from fly-off competition

The FARA procurement, headed by [[Brigadier General]] [[Wally Rugen]], would disburse $15&nbsp;million per candidate selected in the first development phase. The two prototype candidates would each receive $735&nbsp;million to build flying aircraft for the competition.<ref name=DN-181003/> In April 2019, the Army awarded candidate design contracts to five manufacturers: [[AVX Aircraft|AVX]]/[[L3Harris Technologies|L3]], [[Bell Helicopter|Bell]], [[Boeing]], [[Karem Aircraft|Karem]], and [[Sikorsky Aircraft|Sikorsky]].<ref name="DN-190423">{{cite news |author=Judson |first=Jen |date=23 April 2019 |title=US Army picks 5 teams to design new attack recon helicopter |url=https://www.defensenews.com/digital-show-dailies/aaaa/2019/04/23/us-army-picks-5-teams-to-design-new-us-army-attack-recon-helicopter/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://archive.today/20190512144828/https://www.defensenews.com/digital-show-dailies/aaaa/2019/04/23/us-army-picks-5-teams-to-design-new-us-army-attack-recon-helicopter/ |archive-date=12 May 2019 |access-date=15 October 2019 |work=Defense News}}</ref> [[MD Helicopters]], which was developing a variant of its [[MD Helicopters MD Explorer|MD902 Explorer]] with a wing to meet the Army's requirements, was not selected for the candidate design phase.<ref>{{cite news |author=Reim |first=Garrett |date=8 April 2019 |title=GAO deals blow to MD Helicopters' FARA prototype bid |url=https://www.flightglobal.com/news/articles/gao-deals-blow-to-md-helicopters-fara-prototype-bid-457308/ |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200924154039/https://www.flightglobal.com/helicopters/gao-deals-blow-to-md-helicopters-fara-prototype-bid/132212.article |archive-date=24 September 2020 |access-date=15 October 2019 |work=FlightGlobal}}</ref>

==Initial candidate designs==
===AVX/L3===
The AVX/L3 candidate design was unveiled at the summit of the [[Army Aviation Association of America]] in April 2019.<ref name=DN-190423/> The design, which AVX/L3 call the Compound Coaxial Helicopter (CCH), uses a side-by-side cockpit with main compound [[coaxial rotors]]; [[ducted fan]]s at the tail provide both forward and reverse thrust.<ref>{{cite web |date=16 April 2019 |title=AVX Aircraft and L3 Technologies unveil design for U.S. Army's FARA-Competitive Prototype |url=https://verticalmag.com/press-releases/avx-aircraft-and-l3-technologies-unveil-design-for-u-s-armys-fara-competitive-prototype/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220407143928/https://verticalmag.com/press-releases/avx-aircraft-and-l3-technologies-unveil-design-for-u-s-armys-fara-competitive-prototype/ |archive-date=7 April 2022 |website=Vertical Mag}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=AVX / L3Harris FARA Helicopter at AUSA 2019 |url=https://www.helis.com/database/news/avx-l3-harris-fara-ausa-2019/?noamp=1 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211203000837/https://www.helis.com/database/news/avx-l3-harris-fara-ausa-2019/?noamp=1 |archive-date=3 December 2021 |website=helis.com}}</ref>

===Bell===
{{main|Bell 360 Invictus}}
The CEO of Textron, Bell's parent company, stated that its FARA candidate design would be based on technology developed for the [[Bell 525 Relentless|525]], rather than a further development of the [[Bell V-280 Valor|V-280 tiltrotor]].<ref name=DN-190423/> In October 2019, Bell announced the [[Bell 360 Invictus|360 Invictus]] as its FARA candidate design, a winged helicopter with a single rotor and ducted tail rotor.<ref>{{cite news |author=Reim |first=Garrett |date=2 October 2019 |title=ANALYSIS: Bell reveals 360 Invictus proposal for US Army contest |url=https://www.flightglobal.com/news/articles/analysis-bell-reveals-360-invictus-proposal-for-us-461210/ |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210121091642/https://www.flightglobal.com/analysis/bell-reveals-360-invictus-proposal-for-us-army-contest/134557.article |archive-date=21 January 2021 |access-date=15 October 2019 |work=FlightGlobal}}</ref>

===Boeing===
{{as of|October 2019}}, Boeing had not released details on its FARA candidate aircraft to the public.<ref>{{cite news |author=Parsons |first=Dan |date=14 October 2019 |title=Stealth rollout: Boeing keeps Army attack helicopter concept secret |url=https://www.verticalmag.com/news/stealth-rollout-boeing-keeps-army-attack-helicopter-concept-secret/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210208024837/https://verticalmag.com/news/stealth-rollout-boeing-keeps-army-attack-helicopter-concept-secret/ |archive-date=8 February 2021 |access-date=15 October 2019 |work=Vertical}}</ref> A Boeing executive declined to state if the recently unveiled Compound Apache would form the basis for the company's FARA candidate design.<ref>{{cite news |author=Reim |first=Garrett |date=17 May 2019 |title=Boeing suggests propulsor, winged AH-64 Apache variant for US Army |url=https://www.flightglobal.com/news/articles/boeing-suggests-propulsor-winged-ah-64-apache-varia-458248/ |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201001135506/https://www.flightglobal.com/helicopters/boeing-suggests-propulsor-winged-ah-64-apache-variant-for-us-army/132727.article |archive-date=1 October 2020 |access-date=15 October 2019 |work=FlightGlobal}}</ref> On February 13, 2020, Boeing released a teaser video and images of its FARA design. It offers stealth features.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.boeing.com/defense/FARA/ |title=Boeing FARA Reveal – March 2020! |work=Boeing |access-date=23 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author=Reim |first=Garett |date=13 February 2020 |title=Boeing teases its US Army FARA design |url=https://www.flightglobal.com/helicopters/boeing-teases-its-us-army-fara-design/136751.article |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200215220220/https://www.flightglobal.com/helicopters/boeing-teases-its-us-army-fara-design/136751.article |archive-date=15 February 2020 |access-date=23 February 2020 |work=FlightGlobal}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author= |date=21 February 2020 |title=Boeing's stealthy approach could yield armed scout win |url=https://www.flightglobal.com/flight-international-opinion/boeings-stealthy-approach-could-yield-armed-scout-win/136869.article |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230926163218/https://www.flightglobal.com/flight-international-opinion/boeings-stealthy-approach-could-yield-armed-scout-win/136869.article |archive-date=26 September 2023 |access-date=23 February 2020 |work=FlightGlobal}}</ref> More details of the Boeing FARA design were revealed on March 3, 2020; it is a three-rotor compound helicopter with tandem seating.<ref>{{cite news |author=Judson |first=Jen |date=3 March 2020 |title=Boeing's future attack recon helicopter has no name but 3 rotor systems |url=https://www.defensenews.com/land/2020/03/03/boeings-future-attack-recon-helicopter-has-no-name-but-3-rotor-systems/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://archive.today/20200303163505/https://www.defensenews.com/land/2020/03/03/boeings-future-attack-recon-helicopter-has-no-name-but-3-rotor-systems/ |archive-date=3 March 2020 |access-date=4 March 2020 |work=Defense News}}</ref>

===Karem===
Karem Aircraft announced in July 2019 it had partnered with [[Northrop Grumman]] and [[Raytheon]] to design its FARA candidate aircraft.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2 July 2019 |title=Karem Aircraft announces FARA Competitive Prototype team |url=https://verticalmag.com/press-releases/karem-aircraft-announces-fara-competitive-prototype-team/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191015181115/https://www.verticalmag.com/press-releases/karem-aircraft-announces-fara-competitive-prototype-team/ |archive-date=15 October 2019 |access-date=15 October 2019 |website=Vertical}}</ref> On October 16, 2019, Karem unveiled its AR40 design, a compound helicopter with a rigid main rotor, a swiveling tail rotor/pusher propeller, and a pivoting wing.<ref>{{cite news |author=Reim |first=Garrett |date=16 October 2019 |title=PICTURES: Karem unveils FARA design for US Army |url=https://www.flightglobal.com/news/articles/pictures-karem-unveils-fara-design-for-us-army-461512/ |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230603090636/https://www.flightglobal.com/defence/karem-unveils-fara-design-for-us-army/134832.article |archive-date=3 June 2023 |access-date=16 October 2019 |work=FlightGlobal}}</ref>

===Sikorsky===
{{main|Sikorsky Raider X}}
Sikorsky stated that its FARA candidate design would incorporate the compound coaxial rotors and [[pusher propeller]] design used on its [[Sikorsky X2]] and [[Sikorsky S-97 Raider|S-97 Raider]]; the S-97 had initially been developed for the Armed Aerial Scout program.<ref name=DN-181003/> In October 2019, Sikorsky unveiled the [[Sikorsky Raider X]], a scaled-up version of the S-97 Raider designed to accommodate the [[General Electric T901]]-900 turboshaft engine, which won the ITEP competition in February 2019.<ref>{{cite news |author=Reim |first=Garrett |date=15 October 2019 |title=Sikorsky unveils Raider X for US Army's FARA contest |url=https://www.flightglobal.com/news/articles/sikorsky-unveils-raider-x-for-us-armys-fara-contes-461478/ |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230131171810/https://www.flightglobal.com/defence/sikorsky-unveils-raider-x-for-us-armys-fara-contest/134808.article |archive-date=31 January 2023 |access-date=15 October 2019 |work=FlightGlobal}}</ref>

==Finalists==
On March 25, 2020, the US Army selected Bell and Sikorsky to move forward to develop flying prototypes.<ref>{{cite news |author=Host |first=Pat |date=25 March 2020 |title=US Army selects Bell, Sikorsky for FARA-CP programme |url=https://www.janes.com/defence-news/news-detail/us-army-selects-bell-sikorsky-for-fara-cp-programme |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210504002922/https://www.janes.com/defence-news/news-detail/us-army-selects-bell-sikorsky-for-fara-cp-programme |archive-date=4 May 2021 |access-date=26 March 2020 |work=Janes}}</ref> In May 2022, budget documents showed that flight testing would be delayed to Fiscal Year 2024, which starts in October 2023.<ref>{{cite news |author=Finnerty |first=Ryan |date=6 May 2022 |title=Army pushes back FARA prototype testing one year |url=https://www.flightglobal.com/helicopters/army-pushes-back-fara-prototype-testing-one-year/148555.article |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220506210022/https://www.flightglobal.com/helicopters/army-pushes-back-fara-prototype-testing-one-year/148555.article |archive-date=6 May 2022 |access-date=6 June 2022 |work=FlightGlobal}}</ref> Deliveries of the GE T901, developed under ITEP and installed in the FARA prototypes, were delayed until November 2022.<ref>{{cite news |author=Eversden |first=Andrew |date=6 April 2022 |title=After delay, engine for Army's FARA prototypes set for November delivery |url=https://breakingdefense.com/2022/04/after-delay-engine-for-armys-fara-prototypes-set-for-november-delivery/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230526151830/https://breakingdefense.com/2022/04/after-delay-engine-for-armys-fara-prototypes-set-for-november-delivery/ |archive-date=26 May 2023 |access-date=6 June 2022 |work=Breaking Defense}}</ref>

=== Cancellation ===
On 8 February 2024, the U.S. Army ended development on the FARA program. According to an Army press release, the decision was made after a "sober assessment of the modern battlefield".<ref name=":0" /> Army Chief of Staff [[Randy George]] stated it was influenced by the use of inexpensive [[Unmanned combat aerial vehicle|unmanned aerial vehicle]] systems in the [[Russo-Ukrainian War]].<ref name="end_Fara_Dev">{{Cite web |last=Judson |first=Jen |date=2024-02-08 |title=US Army spent billions on a new helicopter that now will never fly |url=https://www.defensenews.com/air/2024/02/08/us-army-spent-billions-on-a-new-helicopter-that-now-will-never-fly/ |access-date=2024-02-12 |website=Defense News |language=en}}</ref> Production of the GE T901 engine would also be delayed pending compatibility with the [[Boeing AH-64 Apache]] and [[Sikorsky UH-60 Black Hawk]].<ref name=":0" /> Development on the [[Future Long-Range Assault Aircraft]] (FLRAA) program and its winner, the [[Bell V-280 Valor]], is continuing.<ref name="continue_Flraa">Rocque, Ashley. [https://breakingdefense.com/2024/02/army-cancels-fara-helicopter-program-makes-other-cuts-in-major-aviation-shakeup/ "Army cancels FARA helicopter program, makes other cuts in major aviation shakeup"]. Breaking Defense, 8 February 2024.</ref>

Reactions to the cancellation were mixed, noting that $9 billion had been spent over two decades on multiple cancelled programs, resulting in no replacement, and leaving the Army to rely on existing types to fill the role.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Schogol |first=Jeff |date=2024-02-09 |title=Army cancels armed scout helicopter program yet again |url=https://taskandpurpose.com/news/army-armed-scout-helicopter/ |access-date=2024-03-17 |website=Task & Purpose |language=en-US}}</ref>

